events.description: Siward, Earl of Northumbria, invades Scotland and defeats Macbeth, King of Scotland, somewhere north of the Firth of Forth. This is known as the Battle of Dunsinane.

events.description: Friedrich Barbarossa arrives at Niš, the capital of Serbian King Stefan Nemanja, during the Third Crusade.
events.html: • 1189 – Friedrich Barbarossa arrives at Niš, the capital of Serbian King Stefan Nemanja, during the Third Crusade.

events.description: Georgian–Seljuk wars: At the Battle of Basian the Kingdom of Georgia defeats the Sultanate of Rum.
events.html: • 1202 – Georgian–Seljuk wars: At the Battle of Basian the Kingdom of Georgia defeats the Sultanate of Rum.

events.description: Battle of Bouvines: Philip II of France decisively defeats Imperial, English and Flemish armies, effectively ending John of England's Angevin Empire.
events.html: • 1214 – Battle of Bouvines: Philip II of France decisively defeats Imperial, English and Flemish armies, effectively ending John of England's Angevin Empire.

events.description: According to Edward Gibbon, Osman I invades the territory of Nicomedia for the first time, usually considered to be the founding day of the Ottoman state.
events.html: • 1299 – According to Edward Gibbon, Osman I invades the territory of Nicomedia for the first time, usually considered to be the founding day of the Ottoman state.

events.description: Battle of Bapheus: Decisive Ottoman victory over the Byzantines opening up Bithynia for Turkish conquest.
events.html: • 1302 – Battle of Bapheus: Decisive Ottoman victory over the Byzantines opening up Bithynia for Turkish conquest.

events.description: The Jesuit priest Francis Xavier's ship reaches Japan.
events.html: • 1549 – The Jesuit priest Francis Xavier's ship reaches Japan.

events.description: The English Parliament passes the second Navigation Act requiring that all goods bound for the American colonies have to be sent in English ships from English ports. After the Acts of Union 1707, Scotland would be included in the Act.
events.html: • 1663 – The English Parliament passes the second Navigation Act requiring that all goods bound for the American colonies have to be sent in English ships from English ports. After the Acts of Union 1707, Scotland would be included in the Act.

events.description: Glorious Revolution: The Battle of Killiecrankie is a victory for the Jacobites.
events.html: • 1689 – Glorious Revolution: The Battle of Killiecrankie is a victory for the Jacobites.[1]

events.description: A Royal charter is granted to the Bank of England.
events.html: • 1694 – A Royal charter is granted to the Bank of England.

events.description: The Great Northern War: The first significant victory of the Russian Navy in the naval battle of Gangut against the Swedish Navy near the Hanko Peninsula.
events.html: • 1714 – The Great Northern War: The first significant victory of the Russian Navy in the naval battle of Gangut against the Swedish Navy near the Hanko Peninsula.[2]

events.description: Founding of the U.S. Army Medical Department:  The Second Continental Congress passes legislation establishing "an hospital for an army consisting of 20,000 men."
events.html: • 1775 – Founding of the U.S. Army Medical Department: The Second Continental Congress passes legislation establishing "an hospital for an army consisting of 20,000 men."

events.description: American Revolution: First Battle of Ushant: British and French fleets fight to a standoff.
events.html: • 1778 – American Revolution: First Battle of Ushant: British and French fleets fight to a standoff.

events.description: The first U.S. federal government agency, the Department of Foreign Affairs, is established (it will be later renamed Department of State).
events.html: • 1789 – The first U.S. federal government agency, the Department of Foreign Affairs, is established (it will be later renamed Department of State).

entities.name: Federal government of the United States

events.description: French Revolution: Maximilien Robespierre is arrested after encouraging the execution of more than 17,000 "enemies of the Revolution".
events.html: • 1794 – French Revolution: Maximilien Robespierre is arrested after encouraging the execution of more than 17,000 "enemies of the Revolution".

events.description: Seminole Wars: The Battle of Negro Fort ends when a hot shot cannonball fired by US Navy Gunboat No. 154 explodes the fort's Powder Magazine, killing approximately 275. It is considered the deadliest single cannon shot in US history.
events.html: • 1816 – Seminole Wars: The Battle of Negro Fort ends when a hot shot cannonball fired by US Navy Gunboat No. 154 explodes the fort's Powder Magazine, killing approximately 275. It is considered the deadliest single cannon shot in US history.

events.description: Indian Rebellion: Sixty-eight men hold out for eight days against a force of 2,500 to 3,000 mutinying sepoys and 8,000 irregular forces.
events.html: • 1857 – Indian Rebellion: Sixty-eight men hold out for eight days against a force of 2,500 to 3,000 mutinying sepoys and 8,000 irregular forces.

events.description: Welsh settlers arrive at Chubut in Argentina.
events.html: • 1865 – Welsh settlers arrive at Chubut in Argentina.

events.description: The first permanent transatlantic telegraph cable is successfully completed, stretching from Valentia Island, Ireland, to Heart's Content, Newfoundland.
events.html: • 1866 – The first permanent transatlantic telegraph cable is successfully completed, stretching from Valentia Island, Ireland, to Heart's Content, Newfoundland.

events.description: Second Anglo-Afghan War: Battle of Maiwand: Afghan forces led by Mohammad Ayub Khan defeat the British Army in battle near Maiwand, Afghanistan.
events.html: • 1880 – Second Anglo-Afghan War: Battle of Maiwand: Afghan forces led by Mohammad Ayub Khan defeat the British Army in battle near Maiwand, Afghanistan.

events.description: Vincent van Gogh shoots himself and dies two days later.
events.html: • 1890 – Vincent van Gogh shoots himself and dies two days later.

events.description: Kaiser Wilhelm II makes a speech comparing Germans to Huns; for years afterwards, "Hun" would be a disparaging name for Germans.
events.html: • 1900 – Kaiser Wilhelm II makes a speech comparing Germans to Huns;[3] for years afterwards, "Hun" would be a disparaging name for Germans.

events.description: World War I: The Allies reach the Yser Canal at the Battle of Passchendaele.
events.html: • 1917 – World War I: The Allies reach the Yser Canal at the Battle of Passchendaele.

events.description: The Chicago Race Riot erupts after a racial incident occurred on a South Side beach, leading to 38 fatalities and 537 injuries over a five-day period.
events.html: • 1919 – The Chicago Race Riot erupts after a racial incident occurred on a South Side beach, leading to 38 fatalities and 537 injuries over a five-day period.

events.description: Researchers at the University of Toronto, led by biochemist Frederick Banting, prove that the hormone insulin regulates blood sugar.
events.html: • 1921 – Researchers at the University of Toronto, led by biochemist Frederick Banting, prove that the hormone insulin regulates blood sugar.

events.description: The Geneva Convention of 1929, dealing with treatment of prisoners-of-war, is signed by 53 nations.
events.html: • 1929 – The Geneva Convention of 1929, dealing with treatment of prisoners-of-war, is signed by 53 nations.

entities.name: Geneva Convention on Prisoners of War (1929)

events.description: The animated short A Wild Hare is released, introducing the character of Bugs Bunny.
events.html: • 1940 – The animated short A Wild Hare is released, introducing the character of Bugs Bunny.[4]

events.description: World War II: Allied forces successfully halt the final Axis advance into Egypt.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Allied forces successfully halt the final Axis advance into Egypt.

events.description: In Vatican City, Rome, canonization of Catherine Labouré, the saint whose apparitions of the Virgin Mary originated the worldwide diffusion of the Miraculous Medal.
events.html: • 1947 – In Vatican City, Rome, canonization of Catherine Labouré, the saint whose apparitions of the Virgin Mary originated the worldwide diffusion of the Miraculous Medal.[5][6]

events.description: Initial flight of the de Havilland Comet, the first jet-powered airliner.
events.html: • 1949 – Initial flight of the de Havilland Comet, the first jet-powered airliner.

events.description: Cessation of hostilities is achieved in the Korean War when the United States, China, and North Korea sign an armistice agreement. Syngman Rhee, President of South Korea, refuses to sign but pledges to observe the armistice.
events.html: • 1953 – Cessation of hostilities is achieved in the Korean War when the United States, China, and North Korea sign an armistice agreement. Syngman Rhee, President of South Korea, refuses to sign but pledges to observe the armistice.

events.description: The Austrian State Treaty restores Austrian sovereignty.
events.html: • 1955 – The Austrian State Treaty restores Austrian sovereignty.

events.description: El Al Flight 402 is shot down by two fighter jets after straying into Bulgarian air space. All 58 people on board are killed.
events.html: • 1955 – El Al Flight 402 is shot down by two fighter jets after straying into Bulgarian air space. All 58 people on board are killed.

events.description: The Continental League is announced as baseball's "third major league" in the United States.
events.html: • 1959 – The Continental League is announced as baseball's "third major league" in the United States.

events.description: The Puijo observation tower is opened to the general public at Puijo Hill in Kuopio, Finland.
events.html: • 1963 – The Puijo observation tower is opened to the general public at Puijo Hill in Kuopio, Finland.[7][8]

events.description: Vietnam War: Five thousand more American military advisers are sent to South Vietnam bringing the total number of United States forces in Vietnam to 21,000.
events.html: • 1964 – Vietnam War: Five thousand more American military advisers are sent to South Vietnam bringing the total number of United States forces in Vietnam to 21,000.

events.description: Watergate scandal: The House of Representatives Judiciary Committee votes 27 to 11 to recommend the first article of impeachment (for obstruction of justice) against President Richard Nixon.

events.description: Mayor of Jaffna and former MP Alfred Duraiappah is shot dead.
events.html: • 1975 – Mayor of Jaffna and former MP Alfred Duraiappah is shot dead.

events.description: While landing at Chihuahua International Airport, Aeromexico Flight 230 overshoots the runway. Thirty-two of the 66 passengers and crew on board the DC-9 are killed.
events.html: • 1981 – While landing at Chihuahua International Airport, Aeromexico Flight 230 overshoots the runway. Thirty-two of the 66 passengers and crew on board the DC-9 are killed.[9]

events.description: Black July: Eighteen Tamil political prisoners at the Welikada high security prison in Colombo are massacred by Sinhalese prisoners, the second such massacre in two days.
events.html: • 1983 – Black July: Eighteen Tamil political prisoners at the Welikada high security prison in Colombo are massacred by Sinhalese prisoners, the second such massacre in two days.

events.description: While attempting to land at Tripoli International Airport in Libya, Korean Air Flight 803 crashes just short of the runway. Seventy-five of the 199 passengers and crew and four people on the ground are killed, in the second accident involving a DC-10 in less than two weeks, the first being United Airlines Flight 232.

events.description: The Supreme Soviet of the Belarusian Soviet Republic declares independence of Belarus from the Soviet Union. Until 1996 the day is celebrated as the Independence Day of Belarus; after a referendum held that year the celebration of independence is moved to June 3.
